			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-956883">
									

<p>The researchers at first didn't know what it did or how to recreate it. If you were the researcher who was “saturated” by the chemical, your first reaction would probably be “OH SHIT I'M GOING TO DIE” depending on the SCP instead of “Hmm, I'm goopy or injected with this stuff or inhaled it or whatever. I wonder if it's an antibiotic.” The reason it became a -EX was because they didn't need the mystery SCP and its mysterious yeast anymore to synthesize the compound (after they figured out what it did). They were able to create it using known chemical compounds and practices.<br />
For example, if the Foundation figured out how to reliably make <a href="/scp-148">Telekill</a> or <a href="/scp-500">SCP-500</a> with what they know (instead of dumping ingredients into a blackbox machine like <a href="/scp-914">SCP-914</a>) and “commonly” available materials, then they would become -EXes.</p>

